liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A Tel Aviv hospital has released photos of 85-year-old Yocheved Lifshitz and 79-year-old Nurit Cooper who were released from Hamas captivity overnight. Ettie Ozel, the hospital's VP of Nursing told Reuters the two elderly women were in "good condition". "I was happy to see two women who arrived back with us, all in all in good condition, very emotional, happy," Ms Ozel said. "We took them to the ward where they met their families; great happiness, many tears, a lot of crying, amazing people." Hamas said it released Ms Lifshitz and Ms Cooper on health grounds. Ms Lifshitz is a peace activist who, together with her husband, helped sick Palestinians in Gaza get to hospital for years, her grandson told Reuters. She and her husband, who is still in Hamas captivity, were kidnapped from their home at the Nir Oz kibbutz, close to the border with Gaza in southern Israel, the Israeli prime minister's office said. The two women were the third and fourth hostages to be freed. Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Freed hostages in "good condition", Tel Aviv hospital nurse says

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The IDF says it has continued to carry out small incursions into Gaza to gather intelligence overnight, but it's not the ground offensive the world has been watching out for, the ABC's Middle East correspondent Allyson Horn reports from Israel. But, Israel says a ground manoeuvre is still to come, she told ABC News' Joe O'Brien from the town of Sderot, about 1 kilometre from the Gaza border. "It is certainly not the ground offensive we were expecting at the moment and it's because that has been delayed. "Although Israel says that a ground manouvre will still occur, the US is advising that they need more time mediate and negotiate to find and get the release of those captives, particularly those with dual nationalities." Israeli air strikes into Gaza have massively increased, with over 400 strikes in the last 24 hours, while a small trickle of aid is making its way into Gaza as hospitals run out of basic supplies.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Aerial bombardment of Gaza continues, ground invasion delayed

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: I'm Middle East Correspondent Allyson Horn and I've just arrived in Sderot, which is an Israeli town about 1km from the Gaza border. From here you can see down into the northern strip of Gaza, where hundreds of thousands of people have been warned to evacuate. Lots of media are positioned here to capture images of the Israeli airstrikes, which I can hear continually. They're big, loud booms that reverberate across southern Israel and Gaza. I've also been hearing artillery fire from Israeli troops training. As I've been driving around I've been seeing dozens of troop carriers, trucks and soldiers who are amassed in the south. Interestingly there's been a massive decrease in the number of Hamas rockets being sent into Israel one the last two days. I've heard only one this morning so far.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Observations from Sderot near the Israel-Gaza border

props.alt: Three camera men in press vests stand at the border

children.content: Journalists work in Sderot
(ABC News: Allyson Horn )
I'm Middle East Correspondent Allyson Horn and I've just arrived in Sderot, which is an Israeli town about 1km from the Gaza border.
From here you can see down into the northern strip of Gaza, where hundreds of thousands of people have been warned to evacuate.
Lots of media are positioned here to capture images of the Israeli airstrikes, which I can hear continually. They're big, loud booms that reverberate across southern Israel and Gaza.
I've also been hearing artillery fire from Israeli troops training. As I've been driving around I've been seeing dozens of troop carriers, trucks and soldiers who are amassed in the south.
Interestingly there's been a massive decrease in the number of Hamas rockets being sent into Israel one the last two days. I've heard only one this morning so far.
